<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>A woman who works at the centre in Pinetown, west of Durban, said staff members are worried about their safety following the incident. “If they can overpower a grown man and stab him 15 times, who are we?” She said she did not know what had caused the fight. “I was not at work, but I heard the supervisor was trying to calm the juveniles who were fighting.“I also heard they had a sharp object and started stabbing him, instead of obeying him.” The supervisor was apparently the only worker at the centre when the incident happened, as other workers were protesting outside for a salary increase.The centre is home to 22 juveniles, who are serving sentences for different convictions. A police source said the juveniles had been convicted of crimes ranging from murder and rape to robbery and possession of drugs. Captain Nqobile Gwala said cops were investigating a murder case.